  "prompt": "What happens to the bond between atoms in a metals when they are melted?",
  "response": "When metals are melted, the following changes occur in the bonds between atoms:\n\n1. Metallic bonds remain, but become more flexible\n- The metal atoms' electron sea becomes more mobile\n- Atoms can move more freely relative to each other\n- Bonds are weakened but not completely broken\n\n2. Atomic movement increases\n- Atoms gain more kinetic energy\n- They vibrate and shift positions more easily\n- Bonds become less rigid\n\n3. Crystal structure breaks down\n- Regular, ordered atomic arrangement is disrupted\n- Atoms can slide past each other more readily\n- Metallic lattice structure becomes less defined\n\n4. Electron mobility increases\n- Electrons in the \"electron sea\" become more freely moving\n- This contributes to the liquid metal's ability to conduct electricity\n\n5. Bonding strength decreases\n- Bonds between atoms become weaker\n- Less energy is required to keep atoms separated\n- Atoms can move more independently\n\nThe fundamental metallic bonding mechanism remains, but the bonds become much more flexible and less structured compared to the solid state. This allows the metal to flow and take the shape of its container while maintaining its metallic properties.",
